  "prompt": "What can substitute butter in a brownies recipe?",
  "response": "Substituting butter in a brownie recipe can be done with several alternatives depending on dietary preferences or what you have on hand. Here are some common substitutes:\n\n1. **Vegetable Oil**: Use an equal amount of vegetable oil (e.g., canola, sunflower, or coconut oil) as a 1:1 replacement for butter. This will keep the brownies moist but may slightly alter the texture.\n\n2. **Coconut Oil**: Use refined coconut oil for a neutral flavor or unrefined for a coconut taste. Replace butter with an equal amount of melted coconut oil.\n\n3. **Applesauce**: For a lower-fat option, replace half the butter with unsweetened applesauce (e.g., if the recipe calls for 1 cup butter, use \u00bd cup butter and \u00bd cup applesauce). This will make the brownies denser and slightly chewier.\n\n4. **Greek Yogurt**: Substitute half the butter with an equal amount of plain Greek yogurt to reduce fat while maintaining moisture.\n\n5. **Avocado**: Use mashed avocado as a 1:1 substitute for butter. This adds creaminess and healthy fats but may result in a slightly denser texture.\n\n6. **Olive Oil**: Use a light or mild olive oil in place of butter. It works well in chocolate recipes due to its complementary flavor.\n\n7. **Margarine**: If not avoiding dairy-free options, margarine can be used as a direct substitute for butter in equal amounts.\n\n8. **Nut Butters**: Almond, peanut, or cashew butter can replace butter for a richer, nuttier flavor. Use equal amounts but be mindful of the flavor impact.\n\n9. **Shortening**: Use an equal amount of vegetable shortening, though this may result in a slightly different texture.\n\n10. **Banana**: Mashed ripe banana can replace butter for a healthier option, but it will add sweetness and a banana flavor. Use \u00bd cup mashed banana for every 1 cup of butter.\n\nWhen substituting, keep in mind that the texture and flavor of the brownies may change slightly. For best results, experiment with small batches to find the substitute you prefer!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
